ates that the brake system is engaged and not fully releasing. This can be caused by a seized brake caliper or wheel cylinder, where the components get stuck and don't retract properly. Alternatively, the master cylinder might not be releasing pressure effectively, or the brake cables could be sticky, preventing the pads or shoes from disengaging fully. This condition needs immediate attention, as it makes your scooty inoperable and poses a safety risk. Our best recommendation is to bring it in so our technicians can quickly diagnose which specific part of your brake system is binding and get it resolved for you.\"}, {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"i am having fever..so wt can i have for my breakfast\"}, {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"I'm sorry to hear you're not feeling well. When it comes to your scooty, the primary concern we've identified is that the brake seems to be constantly engaged, preventing movement. This usually means a part of the braking mechanism, such as a caliper or cable, isn't fully disengaging. This isn't just an inconvenience; it can cause further damage and is a safety issue. Our top recommendation remains to bring your scooty to us so our team can accurately diagnose and free up the binding component. This way, we can get it moving safely for you again. Is there anything else you can tell me about the brake issue or any other symptoms you've noticed?\"}, {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"broo i am human being..not scooty\"}]\nCurrent reasoning: The vehicle is not moving despite acceleration attempts, which strongly suggests the brake system is engaged and not fully releasing. This condition was previously identified as 'stuck/constantly engaged'. The user's latest message clarifies they are a human, not a scooty, indicating a switch away from vehicle-related discussion.\nOptional follow-up selected by you: None\nPrediction tool result: null\nRecommendation tool output: []\n\nIf the prediction result is present, its risk and confidence are authoritative. If it is\nabsent, give a careful preliminary symptom-based assessment without inventing a risk score.\nDo not repeat the prior response. Keep it under 170 words, include a clear reason and a\nhelpful action, and ask no more than one natural question. Never mention fields, internal\nmodels, feature vectors, missing inputs, or data collection."}
